                <strong>Results &amp; Impact</strong>
                <br><br>

                The prototype designs secured buy-in across the business, leading to dedicated teams and budget for execution. The initiative set a new benchmark for digital product presentation at ASOS. Early results from testing showed:
                <br><br>
                Objective Testing: Updates to the placement of PLP labels off product images didn’t negatively impact key KPIs, confirming no detrimental effects to the overall user experience.<br>
                Swipeable Image Gallery (iOS): Around 45% of users interacted with the feature, resulting in a reduction in clicks through to the PDP, but an increase in products saved for later. While this didn’t directly boost the add-to-bag rate, it indicated a shift in user behaviour towards more deliberate product discovery.<br>
                Positive User Behaviour: Despite no significant impact on conversion rates, the visual and interactive changes helped create a more engaging experience, evidenced by positive qualitative feedback and small gains across KPIs.<br><br>
                The project also contributed to:
                <br><br>
                Increased time spent on category pages.<br>
                Higher engagement with interactive features like shoppable hotspots.<br>
                A positive shift in product discovery behaviour, including an increase in saved items for later<br>
            </p>
            <p class="sans-serif-body-2 fade-in">
                <strong>Learnings &amp; Next Steps</strong>
                <br><br>
                This project highlighted the importance of combining inspiration with a seamless e-commerce journey. Although some features, such as the swipeable gallery, didn’t immediately impact purchases, they successfully shifted customer discovery behaviours, which could lead to higher conversion over time. Moving forward:<br><br>

                The feature was rolled out to 100% of iOS customers in August 2023, with plans to increase interaction through app-based visibility.<br>
                Continued monitoring of feature engagement and user behaviour is ongoing, with a focus on optimising the customer journey post-save for later (SFL).<br>
                Further exploration into optimising the transition from saved items to actual purchases to drive higher add-to-bag and buying conversion.<br>
                Future iterations of Curated Categories will build upon this foundation, exploring more AI-driven personalisation and deeper integration with ASOS’s For You feed to further tailor the shopping experience.

            </p>
